@realmoney What Many Are Missing? What so many may be missing is that there is a downside to lower interest rates "as far as the eyes can see." While lower interest rates are generally good for the capital markets (by generally raising valuations in a discounted dividend model)
- too low rates for a long period of time can be a profound negative as it can hinder growth because of inaction. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney
And importantly changing market structure (away from active to passive management) causes "buyers to live higher and sellers to live lower." @SquawkCNBC @SullyCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @tomkeene

current fiscal year and a PE ratio of 220x , the company even boasts a catchy stock symbol, SNOW. At current prices, SNOW is the 69th largest market cap in the S&P despite having less trailing revenues ($440 million) of any company in the S&P Index. (Coincidentally, Amazon went

public in 1997 and traded at a market cap of $442 million (the same sales rate of SNOW today!). But it took another 14 years for Amazon's market cap to hit $80 billion (which at the time had already reached $40 billion in sales)) Unfortunately, those with a sense of market

history recognize SNOW, like SPACs, EVs and other "shiny objects" join the pantheon and list of thin reed indicators of speculation that often mark a market top. @FerroTV @saraeisen @carlquintanilla @michaelsantoli @lizclaman @riskreversal @terranovajoe @guyadami
